      <h3><a name="2007-04-02" href="#2007-04-02">
          <font color="#660000">2007-04-02</font></a></h3>
   	

	<div class="posts">
    <a name="5300203790372605386"></a>
    

	<p>
    <div style="clear:both;"></div><h2>OOX: ISO 5&ndash;month Ballot Period Ends September 2, 2007</h2>
<p>From <a href="http://notes2self.net/archive/2007/04/02/Ecma-_2D00_-_2200_Ecma_2D00_376-Office-Open-XML-DIS-ballot-starts-Monday-April_2C00_-2-for-a-period-of-5-months_2200_.aspx">Stephen McGibbon</a>, this word that the ISO/IEC JTC1 ballot on DIS 29500 (Office Open XML as specified in ECMA-376) has begun and the ballot period ends on Sunday, September 2, 2007&nbsp;(Labor Day weekend in the US).</p>
<p>Available materials:</p>
<ul>
<li>ECMA International press release, 2007&ndash;04&ndash;02: <a href="http://www.ecma-international.org/news/PressReleases/PR_TC45_April2007.htm">Office Open XML Reaches Next Step in ISO/IEC Process</a><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </li>
<li>ECMA TC45/2007/006 (57pp. PDF file), 2007&ndash;02&ndash;28: <a href="http://www.ecma-international.org/news/TC45_current_work/Ecma%20responses.pdf">Response Document &mdash; National Body Comments from 30&ndash;Day Review of the Fast Track Ballot for ISO/IEC DIS 29500 (ECMA-376)</a>&nbsp; [If you are uncomfortable with direct links to PDF, you can also find the 305kB Ecma_Responses.pdf file, dated 2007&ndash;04&ndash;02, in <a href="http://www.ecma-international.org/news/TC45_current_work/?C=M;O=D">this directory</a>.&nbsp; This is the&nbsp;only official release of the ECMA response that I am aware of, and I encourage others to refer to this version.&nbsp; I am&nbsp;certain&nbsp;we&rsquo;ll see some pent-up analysis and rhetorical excursions on this material <a href="http://orcmid.com/blog/2007/03/oox-odf-ecma-response-to-iso-comments-i.asp">now that it is available in public</a>.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp; </li>
<li>ECMA, December 2006: <a href="http://www.ecma-international.org/publications/standards/Ecma-376.htm">Standard ECMA-376 Office Open XML File Formats</a>.&nbsp; These are the official documents, freely available to download.&nbsp; PLEASE, PLEASE, PLEASE use these versions, in Zipped PDF or Zipped DOCX (with annexes) as you prefer.&nbsp; These are the easiest to navigate and they have the correct tables of content, hyperlinks, and printed page numbers.&nbsp; Use those in review, verifying and studying the objections of others, and in understanding how these specifications can be applied.&nbsp; <br />&nbsp;&nbsp; <br />Those who have printed out the single PDF that was circulated for the 30&ndash;day ballot will find that their documents with their printed page numbers will work just fine and they can print out just the new front-matter pages if they want to be completely current.</li></ul>
<p>For individuals not participating in National Standards Bodies who have technical contributions and questions for clarification, I am not sure what the best avenue is.&nbsp; I&rsquo;m looking for it too.&nbsp; For constructive discussion, I think that the <a href="http://openxmldeveloper.org/default.aspx">OpenXMLDeveloper.org</a> site may be an useful avenue.&nbsp; </p>
<p>I&rsquo;m not aware of an open-to-the-public (bidirectional) discussion list in ECMA TC45 like the ones for OASIS ODF, but there is an E-mail address for TC45 Feedback (TC45feedback PIGTAIL ecma-international.org) that might work for feedback on specific elements.</p><div class="bjtags">Tags:  <a rel="tag" href="http://technorati.com/tag/orcmid">orcmid</a>, <a rel="tag" href="http://technorati.com/tag/OOX">OOX</a>, <a rel="tag" href="http://technorati.com/tag/Office+Open+XML">Office+Open+XML</a>, <a rel="tag" href="http://technorati.com/tag/ECMA-376">ECMA-376</a>, <a rel="tag" href="http://technorati.com/tag/ISO/IEC+DIS+29500">ISO/IEC+DIS+29500</a>, <a rel="tag" href="http://technorati.com/tag/open+documents">open+documents</a>, <a rel="tag" href="http://technorati.com/tag/document+standards">document+standards</a></div><div style="clear:both; padding-bottom:0.25em"></div>
    </p>
